  "remote_port": 443,
  "prompt": "Is there a maximum limit for a transaction via Net Banking through an SBI account?",
  "response": "Yes, State Bank of India (SBI) imposes certain limits on transactions conducted through Net Banking. These limits vary depending on the type of transaction and the customer's profile. Below are the general details:\n\n### 1. **Transaction Limits Based on Customer Profile**:\n   - **Retail Customers**:\n     - **Third-party fund transfers (NEFT/RTGS/IMPS)**: Up to **\u20b91 crore per day** (subject to daily and per-transaction limits).\n     - **Own account transfers**: Generally, there is no upper limit.\n     - **Bill payments**, **recharge**, and **shopping**: Up to **\u20b91 lakh per day**.\n   - **Corporate/Institutional Customers**:\n     - Higher transaction limits may apply based on the account type and agreement with the bank.\n\n### 2. **Per Transaction Limits**:\n   - **IMPS**: Up to **\u20b92 lakh per transaction**.\n   - **NEFT**: No upper limit, but exceeding \u20b92 lakh requires a higher authentication level (e.g., OTIN).\n   - **RTGS**: Minimum transaction of **\u20b92 lakh**, with no upper limit.\n\n### 3. **Daily Transaction Limits**:\n   - The default daily limit for fund transfers and other transactions is **\u20b91 crore** for retail customers. However, this can be increased upon request, subject to additional authentication and approval.\n\n### 4. **Special Limits for High-Value Transactions**:\n   - For transactions exceeding \u20b91 crore, customers may need to use **OTIN (One-Time Internet PIN)** or other enhanced authentication methods.\n\n### 5. **International Transactions**:\n   - Limits for international transactions (e.g., forex, remittances) are typically lower and vary based on regulatory guidelines and customer-specific arrangements.\n\n### 6. **Upping the Limit**:\n   - Customers can request to increase their daily transaction limits by contacting their branch or submitting a request through SBI\u2019s online banking portal.\n\n### Notes:\n- These limits are subject to change based on regulatory guidelines and bank policies.\n- Always verify the latest limits and terms on the official SBI website or by contacting customer care.\n\nFor accurate and updated information, it\u2019s best to log in to your SBI Net Banking account or consult with your branch.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
